You may want to put on some music or invite friends over for a fashion show to help move along this part of the process. Remember to try on all your clothes, shoes and accessories. Create enough space to make five piles:
Keep. Keep any clothes that you have worn in the last year or have sentimental value (try to keep the sentimental value clothes to a minimum). These clothes should fit well, be in good condition and represent your personal style. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/09/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet1-Version-3.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet1-Version-3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/09/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet1-Version-3.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet1-Version-3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Donate. If you want to have a truly organized closet, then your goal should be to get rid of as many items of clothing as possible. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/cd/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet2-Version-3.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet2-Version-3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/cd/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet2-Version-3.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet2-Version-3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Trash. Trash any mold ridden items or items beyond salvage. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/44/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet3-Version-3.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet3-Version-3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/44/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet3-Version-3.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet3-Version-3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Alter. Set aside those clothes you want to keep that need a little TLC like alterations or sewing. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6e/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet4-Version-3.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet4-Version-3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6e/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet4-Version-3.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet4-Version-3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Sell. Sell the clothes that are still current or valuable that do not flatter your shape, are not the right size or no longer reflect the image you want to project. Check out local consignment shops or online storefronts that specialize in buying and selling used clothes. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b4/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet5-Version-3.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet5-Version-3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b4/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet5-Version-3.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-2Bullet5-Version-3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Decide which clothes you will store. You should store the clothes that you won't be wearing for a while because they aren't seasonally appropriate. Then decide which clothes will go back into your closet and which clothes will be stored in a dresser or other location. If you have the space to hang everything, hang everything. If you really want to step it up a notch, you can use different colored hangers to mark a different type of clothing. Start by hanging up all your clothes by type (tank tops, shirts, pants, skirts, dresses, etc.) and color. If you really get into the organization process you can sub-divide the clothing types further (short-sleeved shirts, long-sleeved shirts, blouses, dress pants, casual pants, etc.). Put additional clothes in other parts of your closet. Boxes with lids can be stacked on upper shelves all the way to the ceiling to maximize storage space. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2c/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-4Bullet1-Version-3.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-4Bullet1-Version-3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2c/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-4Bullet1-Version-3.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-4Bullet1-Version-3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you have room for a dresser, consider putting one in your closet. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e2/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-4Bullet2-Version-3.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-4Bullet2-Version-3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e2/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-4Bullet2-Version-3.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-4Bullet2-Version-3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Don't waste the space under your hanging clothes. Add shoe storage, clothing bins or even another shelf or hanging pole to double storage. The clothes that you put in the bins should be used less frequently than the clothes you hang up. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ed/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-4Bullet3-Version-3.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-4Bullet3-Version-3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ed/Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-4Bullet3-Version-3.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Master-Bedroom-Closet-Step-4Bullet3-Version-3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
